occurrences.line_text: There did they find, that which they did not feare,
Though not his feare; for nought may feare disswade;
Though not his feare; for nought may feare disswade;
Knowing his fatall hand by former feare;
Much feared I to haue bene quite abhord,
That his beheast they feared, as tyrans law,
That seemed from some feared foe to fly,
That feared chance from her to turne away;
And to my foe betrayd, when least I feared ill.
Yet feared least his boldnesse should offend,
I feared loue: but they that loue do liue,
For still she feared to be ouerhent,
Much feared he, least ought did ill betide
Two things he feared, but the third was death;
And now made better speed, t'escape his feared foe.
Feared in vaine, sith meanes ye see there wants theretoo.
Ne each of other feared fraud or tort,
Ooraxes, feared for great Cyrus fate;
Now lesse she feared that same fatall read,
The daungerous state, in which she stood, she feared
Sometime she feared, least some hard mishap
Nought feared they, what he could do, or say,
Are dreadded most, and feared for their powre:
Yet him nought terrifide, that feared nothing ill.
With stronger death, and feared their decay,
Ne ought was feared of his certaine harmes:
That much he feared, least reprochfull blame
The fearefull Dwarfe:) this is no place for liuing men.
Thus ill bestedd, and fearefull more of shame,
Whom suddenly he wakes with fearefull frights,
The fearefull Shepheard often there aghast
Yet of those fearefull women none durst rize,
His fearefull friends weare out the wofull night,
Soone as she parted thence, the fearefull twaine,
And with faire fearefull humblesse towards him shee came.
Such fearefull fit assaid her trembling hart,
The fearefull Dame all quaked at the sight,
My fearefull flesh did tremble at their strife,
Doth roll adowne the rocks, and fall with fearefull drift.
But I more fearefull, or more luckie wight,
And his fresh bloud did frieze with fearefull cold,
As fearefull fowle, that long in secret caue
But soone through suff'rance grow to fearefull end;
Fly therefore, fly this fearefull stead anon,
But roughly him bespake. Thou fearefull foole,
His fearefull face in time of greatest storme,
But are into these fearefull shapes disguiz'd
But Penda, fearefull of like desteny,
When the two fearefull women saw, they grew
Threatning to swallow vp my fearefull life?
The fearefull damzell, with incessant paines:
Like as a fearefull Doue, which through the raine,
That fearefull Ladie fled from him, that ment
The fearefull end of his auengement sad,
What end vnto that fearefull Damozell,
Whom when the fearefull Damzell nigh espide,
Fled fearefull Daphne on th'ï¿½gï¿½an strond,
The fearefull Chorle durst not gainesay, nor doe,
Like as a fearefull Partridge, that is fled
For fire in earnest, ran with fearefull speed,
And after him eke fearefull Trompart sped;
He in a bush did hide his fearefull hed,
Ne stayd his flight, nor fearefull agony,
The fearefull boy so greedily pursew,
Ah, how the fearefull Ladies tender hart
Ensewd, whose noyance fild the fearefull sted,
Full of sad signes, fearefull to liuing sight;
For Amoret right fearefull was and faint,
Which when as fearefull Amoret perceiued,
For from his fearefull eyes two fierie beames,
From fearefull cowards, entrance to forstall,
Much more deformed fearefull vgly were,
With fearefull shadowes of deformed night,
And at her strooke with puissance fearefull fell;
Is broken with some fearefull dreames affright,
With that she waked, full of fearefull fright,
But th'other still pursu'd the fearefull Mayd;
For her beginning a more fearefull fray,
And many fearefull obiects to them to present.
In which the fearefull ewftes do build their bowres,
Her fearefull speaches nought he did regard,
There then began a fearefull cruell fray
The fearefull Lady to her father deare,
And to betake him selfe to fearefull flight;
A monstrous Dragon, full of fearefull vglinesse.
In fearefull darkenesse, furthest from the skie,
The fearefull swayne beholding death so nie,
Being alreadie dead with fearefull fright.
Him thether eke for all his fearefull threat
And like a fearefull dog him followed through the land.
The Damzell pauzd, and then thus fearefully;
Which his right hand vnarmed fearefully did wield.
And eke the Ladie fearefully aghast,
So from the ground she fearelesse doth arise,
Thereby so fearelesse, and so fell he grew,
To whom the Palmer fearelesse answered;
With stately steps, and fearelesse countenance,
That still the life stood fearelesse of her foe:
Where fearelesse I to sleepe me downe did lay.
Eftsoones she flew vnto his fearelesse hand,
Consent, that I who stood all fearelesse free,
Vnto the wall his way did fearelesse take,
Vnder the Idols feete in fearelesse bowre,
The better to confirme her fearelesse confidence.
Into the field, as if he fearelesse were,
Fearelesse, who ought did thinke, or ought did say,
Fearelesse of foes that mote his peace molest;
Fearelesse of ought, that mote her peace molest,
Now drowned in the depth of sleepe all fearelesse lay.
Fearelesse of foes, or fortunes wrackfull yre,
Be but as bugs to fearen babes withall,
Words fearen babes. I meane not thee entreat
Captiu'd to fortune and frayle worldly feares,
Ne let vaine feares procure your needlesse smart,
But followes her farre off, ne ought he feares,
Nor life in limbe: and to increase his feares,
In which we long time without gealous feares,
For not of nought these suddeine ghastly feares
In stead of sleepe thou sendest troublous feares,
And to be free from hard restraint and gealous feares.
In vaine he feares that, which he cannot shonne:
Phrixus and Helle from their stepdames feares,
A thousand feares, that loue-sicke fancies faine to fynde.
But stood long staring on him, mongst vncertaine feares.
Wrapt in great dolours and in deadly feares,
Forgetfull of her owne, to minde his feares:
Her selfe now past the perill of her feares.
Why fearest thou, that canst not hope for thing,
And fearest not, that more thee hurten might,
Ne feareth he henceforth that foe of his,
By which he feareth euill happen may:
And chaste so fiercely after fearfull flight,
Her fearfull feete towards the bowre she moued;
Yet both doe striue their fearfulnesse to faine.
Where soone he slumbred, fearing not be harm'd,
And euery loup fast lockt, as fearing foes despight.
As fearing euill, that pursewd her fast;
Till enuious Men fearing their rules decay,
Fearing least from her cage the wearie soule would flit.
Some fearing shriekt, some being harmed hould,
Fearing least she your loues away should woo,
And there he threw her in, nought feeling, ne nought fearing.
Fearing least if she should him freely set,
Both strongly arm'd, as fearing one another;
Some fearing fraud, some fraudulently fayning,
Then fearing any foeman there to meete:
Vnarm'd, as fearing neither foe nor frend,
Yet fearing death, and next to death the lacke
Fearing least he at length the raines would lend
Fearlesse of fortunes chaunge or enuies dread,
Rest is their feast, and all things at their will;
And fed her fat with feast of offerings,
With which he swallowd vp excessiue feast,
Of whom he meanes his bloudie feast to make,
And bloudie mouthed with late cruell feast.
Not vnto such, as could him feast againe,
Then all the people, as in solemne feast,
What needs me tell their feast and goodly guize,
And made great feast to solemnize that day;
And solemne feast proclaimd throughout the land,
Thus fairely she attempered her feast,
An yearely solemne feast she wontes to make
But to the mighty victour yields a bounteous feast.
And of his bowels made his bloudie feast:
Amidst the bridale feast, whilest euery man
And of the bloodie feast, which sent away
A solemne feast, with publike turneying,
Where making ioyous feast theire daies they spent
To ioyous feast and other gentle play;
And now by this their feast all being ended,
In which he wont the relickes of his feast,
He part of his small feast to her would share;
To feast and frollicke; nathemore would she
From greedy hold of that his blouddy feast:
It fortun'd then, a solemne feast was there
So both agreed, that this their bridale feast
Liues still: and to this feast with Neptunes seed was dight.
And now by this the feast was throughly ended,
To tell the glorie of the feast that day,
With whom great feast and goodly glee he fond,
Vppon some fowle, that should her feast prepare;
Making great feast and ioyous merriment,
Where goodly glee and feast to them she made,
And the frutes of the forrest was their feast:
With all the courteous glee and goodly feast,
To make a common feast, & feed with gurmandize.
For your meane food shall be my daily feast,
Of whom high Ioue wont whylome feasted bee,
And fairely feasted, as so noble knights she ought.
And gaine a feastfull guerdon of their toyle,
As he this way comming from feastfull glee,
Feasting and courting both in bowre and hall;
And dayly feasting both in bowre and hall,
Vaine feasts, and idle superfluity:
In beds, in bowres, in banckets, and in feasts:
and feasts the Sea-gods all.
Iustice sate high ador'd with solemne feasts,
And solemne feasts and giusts ordain'd therefore.
But by your wondrous worth and warlike feat
That Albion had conquered first by warlike feat.
Like as a Smith that to his cunning feat
To graunt him that aduenture for his former feat.
Many faire pourtraicts, and many a faire feate,
And feates of armes did wisely vnderstand.
The warlike feates of both those knights to see.
In warlike feates th'expertest man aliue,
As feates of armes, and loue to entertaine,
And for his warlike feates renowmed is,
To heare the warlike feates, which Homere spake
Well knowen by his feates, and famous ouer all.
For he in slights and iugling feates did flow,
Thenceforth the feather in her loftie crest,
And deckt himselfe with feathers youthly gay,
She gins her feathers foule disfigured
Headed with flint, and feathers bloudie dide,
That warlike feats doest highest glorifie.
For his bold feats and hardy confidence,
Which haue full many feats aduenturous
Traind vp in feats of armes and knightlinesse;
And all her filthy feature open showne,
Which when as forme and feature it does ketch,
Which the faire feature of her limbs did hyde,
Through secret vnderstanding of their feature.
To tell the feature of each goodly face.
The maker selfe resembling in her feature?
Bewrayd the signes of feature excellent:
And praise the feature of her goodly face,
And gan her forme and feature to expresse,
Features of beautie, and all shapes select,
But both his hands most filthy feculent,
A thousand yong ones, which she dayly fed,
And fed with words, that could not chuse but please,
And fed her fat with feast of offerings,
And Tityus fed a vulture on his maw;
She fed her wound with fresh renewed bale;
Whom still she fed, whiles they were weake & young,
For happie life to all, which thereon fed,
And gazers sense with double pleasure fed,
Thus when she had his eyes and senses fed
Therewith a while she her flit fancy fed,
With such selfe-pleasing thoughts her wound she fed,
Vpon that milke-white Palfreyes carkas fed,
Quite of all hope, wherewith he long had fed
With wonder of her beauty fed their hungry vew.
That fed on liuing flesh, & druncke mens vitall blood.
With which he fed her fancie, and entysd
The whiles their Gotes vpon the brouzes fed,
And for her sake her cattell fed a while,
And fed on fodder, to beguile her sight.
Then with vaine poemes weeds to haue their fancies fed.
With which she from her childhood had bene fed.
Of men and beasts; and fed on fleshly gore,
But certes was with milke of Wolues and Tygres fed.
Witnesse th'exceeding fry, which there are fed,
He might not with immortall food be fed,
For I him find to be too proudly fed.
And drawne of cruell steedes, which he had fed
That falling on his mother earth he fed:
On which she fed, and gnawed hungrily,
Long fed his greedie eyes with the faire sight
Ne fed on flesh, ne euer of wyld beast
Here by the Gods, and fed with heauenly sap,
And shepheards singing to their flockes, that fed,
Beside them fed, and nipt the tender bloomes:
Tho hauing fed his fill, he there besyde
But after he had fed, yet did he stay,
Their tender flocks, now being fully fed,
Of courtly fauour, fed with light report,
And with delight his greedy fancy fed,
But fed on spoile and booty, which they made
In their defence, nor would for gold or fee
To them by equall shares in equall fee:
And cleeped him his liege, to hold of him in fee.
And idle offers of thy golden fee;
And his broad braunches, laden with rich fee,
And her knights seruice ought, to hold of her in fee.
Will chalenge yond same other for my fee:
Of beauties praise, and yeeld the fayrest her due fee.
And eke of Lordship, with both land and fee:
Yet is the paine thereof much greater then the fee.
Did equally bequeath his lands in fee,
And gaue to them great liuing and large fee:
What else they haue, is all the Tyrants fee;
Nor land nor fee, for hyre of his good deede,
And thousand thankes to Calidore for fee
As in his fee, with peaceable estate,
Are Venus Damzels, all within her fee,
Shed thy faire beames into my feeble eyne,
All striuing to infixe their feeble stings,
O then too weake and feeble was the forse
While flashing beames do daze his feeble eyen,
Did her content to please their feeble eyes,
And all that drunke thereof, did faint and feeble grow.
And mightie strong was turnd to feeble fraile.
Through that fraile fountaine, which him feeble made,
Whiles yet his feeble feet for faintnesse reeld,
That on a staffe his feeble steps did frame,
Whose feeble thighes, vnhable to vphold
That this her knight was feeble, and too faint;
Wont on a staffe his feeble steps to stay,
Or doen thy feeble feet vnweeting hither stray?
The feeble soule departing hence away.
His feeble sence, and too exceeding shyne.
Whose sight my feeble soule doth greatly cheare:
O gently come into my feeble brest,
The yielding aire, which nigh too feeble found
His nigh forwearied feeble feet did slide,
Did grone, as feeble so great load to lift;
There eke my feeble barke a while may stay,
Vprose with hastie ioy, and feeble speed
That feeble eyes your glory may behold,
That with a staffe his feeble steps did stire,
Her feeble pulse, to proue if any drop
With feeble hands then stretched forth on hye,
And feeble nature cloth'd with fleshly tyre,
My feeble courage, and my hart oppresse,
But on a staffe her feeble steps did stay;
Does charme her louers, and the feeble sprightes
From that, which feeble nature couets faine;
His feeble feet directed to the cry;
And by your powre protect his feeble cace.
And all decrepit in his feeble corse,
To have diuided. Tho when feeble age
So feeble is mans state, and life vnsound,
Thought to haue mounted, but his feeble vaines
Who by self-feeling of her feeble sexe,
His feeling words her feeble sence much pleased,
When feeble nature felt her selfe opprest,
Betwixt her feeble armes her quickly keight,
My feeble brest of late, and launched this wound wyde.
Her chearefull words much cheard the feeble spright
Doe tosse, that it will stonne thy feeble braines,
The feeble Britons, broken with long warre,
Wherein my feeble barke is tossed long,
For else my feeble vessell crazd, and crackt
So feeble is the powre of fleshly arme.
Some litle life his feeble sprites emong;
His bootelesse bow in feeble hand vpcaught,
In easie couch his feeble limbes to rest,
His feeble hart wide launched with loues cruell wound.
His feeble eyne, with too much brightnesse dazed,
Vnto her sonne, that lay in feeble state;
But yet what so my feeble Muse can frame,
The feeble senses wholly did confound,
His feeble steps, which shrunke, when hard theron he lay.
And with her feeble feet did moue a comely pace.
Repentance feeble, sorrowfull, and lame:
Sir Triamond at last full faint and feeble stood.
Her feeble ioynts layd eke a downe to rest;
And feeble hope hung all this while suspence,
In feeble Ladies tyranning so sore;
This feeble brest endured hath, but none
To which I boldly came vpon my feeble feete.
The one right feeble through the euill rate
Passing the measure of my feeble powre,
Which fayled oft through faint and feeble plight:
And feeble spirit inly felt refection;
Then to defend the feeble in their right,
That none of them the feeble ouerren,
So feeble skill of perfect things the vulgar has.
But bread and water, or like feeble thing,
And feeble spirits, that gan faint and reele,
Which carry colours faire, that feeble eies misdeeme.
Yet for the feeble Ladies sake, full loth
And wend abrode, though feeble and forlorne,
Did vse, his feeble body to sustaine;
So faint and feeble were, that they ne might
Vpon the ground with feeble feete he trode,
The which was fall'n into this feeble case,
Yet heauens them selues, that fauour feeble rights,
Which may her feeble leaues with comfort glade.
And her foundation forst, and feebled quight,
Which mote the feebled Britons strongly flancke
Through feeblenesse, which all his limbes oppressed has.
Both for great feeblesse, which did oft assay
Feebly she shriekt, but so feebly indeed,
Feebly she shriekt, but so feebly indeed,
Yet for to feed his fyrie lustfull eye,
Why do ye lenger feed on loathed light,
Mine eyes no more on vanitie shall feed,
His office was, the hungry for to feed,
Did feed his eyes, and fild his inner thought.
Whylome her louers, which her lusts did feed,
To feed her humour with his pleasing stile,
It is, ï¿½ Nurse, which on my life doth feed,
But feed on shadowes, whiles I die for food,
And feed her fancy with delightfull chaunge:
Ne euer is he wont on ought to feed,
And feed it selfe with selfe-consuming smart?
Ne feed on ought, the which doth bloud containe,
Of dreaded daunger might his doubtfull humour feed.
But on the labours of poore men to feed,
To make a common feast, & feed with gurmandize.
They prayd him sit, and gaue him for to feed
No better doe I weare, no better doe I feed.
And feed an hundred flocks, there now not one he found.
To feede her foolish humour, and vaine iolliment.
And turned vpsidowne, to feede his eye
That feeds on womens flesh, as others feede on gras.
On her faire face so did he feede his fill,
Now gan to feede on hope, which she before
To feede the humour of her maladie;
For beasts and foules to feede vpon for their repast.
Vnto some place, where they mote rest and feede,
And in some stable neare did set him vp to feede.
He feedes vpon the cooling shade, and bayes
Which feedes each liuing plant with liquid sap,
And his fraile eye with spoyle of beautie feedes;
And euermore himselfe with comfort feedes,
And feedes on all the carkasses, that die
She feedes on her owne maw vnnaturall,
To feeding of her priuate fire, which boyld
With thousand thoughts feeding her fantasie,
And feeding on the bayt of his owne bane.
And who with gracious bread the hungry feeds,
That feeds on womens flesh, as others feede on gras.
That inly feeds it selfe with thoughts vnkind,
Feele my heart perst with so great agonie,
That hope of new good hap he gan to feele;
The saluage nation feele her secret smart,
Then that I feele, and harbour in mine hart:
But trembling feare did feele in euery vaine;
Wherein he fell, or sharper edge did feele,
Her voluntarie paine, and feele some secret ease.
Whiles the sad pang approching she does feele,
With his faire garment: then gan softly feele
Right sowre, & feele the law, the which thou hast defast.
So slyly, that she did not feele the wound,
Did feele his pulse, she knew their staied still
Ne in their frosen hearts feele kindly flame:
Began to faint, and feele their corage cold.
And made it seeme to feele her grieuous paine,
Let him feele hardnesse of thy heauie arme:
(Sayd she) yet now I gin new life to feele,
And when I gin to feele decay of might,
And feele compassion of his euill plight
And life to feele, that long for death had sought;
For whom so faire a Lady feeles so sore a wound.
Ne feeles the thorns and thickets pricke her tender toes.
That feeles the warmth of sunny beames reflection,
Soone as he feeles it mollifide with heat,
Like to a flowre, that feeles no heate of sunne,
Her feeling speeches some compassion moued
Faire feeling words he wisely gan display,
As feeling wondrous comfort in her weaker eld.
Of feeling pleasures, with which day and night
Where feeling one close couched by her side,
His feeling words her feeble sence much pleased,
Feeling her leape out of her loathed nest,
And feeling by his pulses beating rife,
Those feeling wordes so neare the quicke did goe,
Through secret feeling of his generous spright,
Till feeling life to fayle, it fell, and deadly slept.
Hath worne to nought, now feeling sommers might,
And fell away, as feeling secret blame.
And there he threw her in, nought feeling, ne nought fearing.
She feeling him thus bite vpon the bayt,
And sorrowes feeling, yet with conscience
And gan to stretch his limbs; which feeling ill
That like an Hauke, which feeling her selfe freed
Feeling some curre behinde his heeles to bite,
So feelingly her case she did complaine,
Till that infernall feend with foule vprore
Whose corage when the feend perceiu'd to shrinke,
Here haunts that feend, and does his dayly spoyle,
For dread of that huge feend emprisond be
Whom when the damned feend so fresh did spy,
But yet at last, when as the direfull feend
That cursed man, that cruell feend of hell,
An vgly feend, more fowle then dismall day,
Thereat the feend his gnashing teeth did grate,
And euery feend his busie paines applide,
That dreadfull feend, which did behind him wayt,
Or hellish feend raysd vp through diuelish science.
Was fled afore, affraid of him, as feend of hell.
That of that feend was rent without remorse:
Fiercely he flew vpon that wicked feend,
Now like a Gyant, now like to a feend,
That when the wicked feend his Lord tormented,
The one a feend, the other an incarnate deuill.
Certes some hellish furie, or some feend
In sacrifize vnto that cursed feend:
A dreadfull feend, with fowle deformed looke,
She flew at him, like to an hellish feend,
But then the feend her selfe more fiercely reard
A dreadfull feend of gods and men ydrad,
To that foule feend, who dayly doth attend
In the next brooke, by who[m] that feend shold be fordonne.
Nor any wicked feend, that mote offend
To reskue her, but when he saw the feend,
And fared like a feend, right horrible in hew.
Infernall Hags, Centaurs, feendes, Hippodames,
Dragons, and Minotaures, and feendes of hell,
As one aghast with feends or damned sprights,
Of feends infernall flockt on euery side,
And thousand feends that doe them endlesse paine
But either hellish feends, or powres on hie:
With hellish feends, or Furies mad vprore,
From other couetous feends it to defend,
By euery fornace many feends did bide,
